Four children died after eating something at a dump this past weekend. The police haven’t released the autopsy results yet but, in the meantime, it’s generally accepted that whatever they ate killed them. And government blamed it on the local community. A municipal spokesperson said that illegal dumping was the problem – not the fact that there are no skips or rubbish collection services in that part of the Eastern Cape township where most people from the surrounding informal settlements are currently being relocated – and where these children met their deaths. It’s callous. They were children. The youngest was...